SIMPLE: nonce
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Nonce
<hw>Nonce</hw> <pr>(n⟦ocr⟧ns)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[For the
<ets>nonce</ets>, OE. for the <ets>nones</ets>, a corruption of for then
<ets>ones</ets>, where <pos>n.</pos> in <ets>then</ets> is a relic of
AS. <ets>m</ets> in <ets>⟦edh⟧am</ets>, dat. of the article and
demonstrative pronoun, E. <ets>the</ets>. See <er>For</er>,
<er>Once</er>, and <er>The</er>.]</ety> <def>The one or single occasion;
the present call or purpose; -- chiefly used in the phrase <col><b>for
the nonce</b></col>, i. e. <sig>for the present time</sig>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The miller was a stout carl for the <qex>nones</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And that he calls for drink, I 'll have prepared him⟦br⟧
A chalice for the <qex>nonce</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Nonce word</b></col>, <cd>⟦ldquo⟧a word apparently
employed only <xex>for the nonce</xex>⟦rdquo⟧.</cd> <rj><au>Murray (New
English Dict.).</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>noncellular</ent>⟦br⟧
